      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are absolutely right to dig deeper; looking at the floor framing is like checking the foundation of a house to see if the walls are holding it up or just sitting on top of it.\n\nWhen you enter the basement, you are looking for the **joists** (or rafters) that run perpendicular to the wall. If you see a thick, heavy wooden beam running directly underneath the wall, that is your **load-bearing wall**. It is the \"skeleton\" of the house, and if you knock on it, you will hear that deep, resonant *thwack* again because the wood is dense and massive.\n\nIf you see only thin, vertical wooden studs spaced apart (usually 16 inches on center), that is a **partition wall**. These are just the vertical supports for the drywall and ceiling, and they will make a sharp, hollow *ping* when tapped.\n\nAlso, look for the **floor joists** running parallel to the wall. If the wall is load-bearing, the floor joists will be spaced closer together (often every 16 inches) because they need to support the weight of the entire floor above. If the wall is just a partition, the floor joists",
